article.headline: Blazers' Anderson suffers concussion in first quarter
article.linkText: Wallace, Blazers keep Grizzlies winless on season
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Momentarily stunned by injuries, the Portland Trail Blazers turned to their deep bench.
Pippen

Scottie Pippen and Antonio Daniels stepped in with 16 points each as the Blazers overcame a spate of injuries to beat the winless Memphis Grizzlies 94-88 Wednesday night. The Blazers were hurt just 2 minutes into the game when they lost Derek Anderson to a concussion. Starting forward Bonzi Wells was a last-minute scratch with a sore right foot, and center Arvydas Sabonis sat out with a strained right hamstring. "The guys who came off the bench did an excellent job,'' Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "Missing Bonzi, D.A. and Arvydas doesn't matter. It doesn't matter to me who's on the court as long as the guys that are out there play hard.'' The Grizzlies (0-5) are the NBA's only winless team. Pau Gasol, last season's Rookie of the Year, led all scorers with 23 points for Memphis. Jason Williams added 19 points and 11 assists. Rasheed Wallace had 18 points and eight rebounds for the Trail Blazers (2-3), who snapped a three-game losing streak. Dale Davis had 10 points and 13 rebounds. Anderson, averaging 14 points per game, fell hard under the Grizzlies' basket. He was prone for several minutes but remained alert as trainers attended to him. Anderson was taken to Southwest Washington Medical Center where he was expected to be held overnight for observation. Wells, meanwhile, has struggled this season with blisters on his feet. The Trail Blazers would not say specifically whether that's what caused him to miss the game. The Blazers led most of the first half until the Grizzlies started making their move. Taking control of the tempo, Gasol put Memphis ahead 42-41 on a slam dunk with 3:37 left in the second quarter. The Blazers had a chance to grab the lead back, but Davis missed a pair of free throws with 2:50 left and the Grizzlies went on to lead 48-43 at halftime. Pippen's 22-foot jumper tied it at 51 in the third quarter, and the Trail Blazers reclaimed the lead when Davis' jumper made it 53-51 with 8:04 to go. The Grizzlies went on a 10-2 run to go up 61-57 with 4:50 left in the third quarter, but Ruben Patterson's dunk with 33 seconds left gave the Blazers a 70-69 lead. Jeff McInnis put Portland ahead again 72-71 with 9:38 to go in the game to spark a 12-0 run capped by Zach Randolph's dunk. That made it 82-71 with 5:16 left -- and the Blazers led the rest of the way. "They just picked up the intensity. They got active with their hands, they had hands everywhere,'' Memphis coach Sidney Lowe said. "Hands on the ball, hands on the body. Hands everywhere.'' Pippen played 37 minutes, his most this season. The 16-year veteran had surgery on his right knee during the offseason and has been slow to recover. He sat out the preseason. "It gave me an opportunity to get out and get back into the flow of playing again,'' Pippen said. "I'm ready to push the minutes.'' Sabonis strained his right hamstring in Portland's 96-79 loss to Denver on Saturday. The 7-foot-3 center, returning to the NBA after taking last season off, was listed as day-to-day and was expected to make the team's upcoming four-game road trip. Last season, the Grizzlies lost eight straight before their first win. They almost got their first one on Monday when they took San Antonio into overtime, but ended up losing 103-101. Portland was also coming off a tough 98-95 overtime loss to the Lakers on Sunday. The Trail Blazers' lone previous win this season was in their season opener against Los Angeles, playing without Shaquille O'Neal and Rick Fox. Game notes
Lowe played for high school coaching great Morgan Wootten, who retired Wednesday after 46 years. Wootten was the winningest coach in high school basketball, with a 1,274-192 record. "I called him a couple of times on issues, and I knew I could do that because he always knew the right things to say,'' Lowe said. ... Action Sports Cable Network, a regional 24-hour sports network, went out of business Monday. If the Trail Blazers don't find another outlet for this season's 27 scheduled ASCN games, they would have the fewest televised games in the NBA. ... Gasol has scored at least 20 points in all five games.
